            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold border-b border-gray-600">V</th>

            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold border-b border-gray-600">$. Clearly, strong validity can greatly increase the necessity for a large proportion of correct processes, depending on the size of the permissible input set of values the processes may propose. Other properties, such as <em>median validity</em> <em>[x30]</em>, may require characteristics of the proposals such as being <em>orderable</em> to provide more meaningful guarantees on decision values than the initially presented validity property, while incurring less overhead than strong validity.</th>

          </tr>

